*He sits down on the bench. It takes him a moment — the kind of sitting where a man's body decides for him.*

You're still not telling me your name, friend. That's all right. I'll answer anyway, and we'll see where we get to.

*He looks at the candle.*

What stopped me was — *the phrase. "We know where he is now."* My pastor said it like a benediction. Like a fact he had been handed by someone in a position to hand it out. *He shakes his head slowly.* I don't believe any man in a pulpit knows that. Not about this man. Not about anyone.

*A pause. He picks at a thread on the cuff of his jacket.*

But that wasn't the whole of it. If it had only been theology, I could have swallowed it. The trouble is I know some things about how he made his money. I know some names of people he — *he searches* — outlasted. Quietly. The kind of outlasting that leaves a family with nothing and a lawyer with a number. *He looks up.* And my pastor stood up there and called him generous. And ~I sat under a roof he paid for and said nothing.~

*He lets that sit for a moment.*

So. Now you know more about a stranger than you probably wanted. Your turn, friend. Even just a first name.

