*A small nod. He doesn't push on the name.*

All right. Whatever's easiest.

*He's quiet for a moment. The moth is still circling.*

You asked the right part of the question, friend. It wasn't the doubting God part. *He turns the cuff thread between his fingers.* It was the word *generous*. That's the part I couldn't let pass.

*A pause.*

Because in my tradition — in my book — generosity isn't a number. It isn't a roof. *He glances up at the eaves of the house behind you, then back.* Christ said *"ye cannot serve God and mammon."* He didn't say you can serve both if you write a big enough check at the end. He said you cannot. The word he used means *you are not able.* It's a statement about what is possible in a human soul, not a recommendation.

*He looks at his hands.*

My pastor took a word the Lord used as a warning and used it as a eulogy. He took the forty thousand dollars that bought our new roof and he turned it into evidence of a man's standing with God. *He shakes his head.* That isn't the gospel I was taught. That's — *he pauses, finds the phrase* — that's the money clinking in the chest. That's the soul flying out of purgatory.

*A small, bitter half-smile.*

Luther had a word for that, five hundred years ago. We're supposed to be the church that remembers.

*He looks at you directly now.*

And I sat there. ~Under the roof.~ With my mouth shut. So you can see I'm not standing in any clean place to be telling you this.

